results.notes: Three fruitbodies growing in an open space in short grass/moss, 15-20 yards from the nearest old oak. I have found this species/organism at this location in the past, but closer to the oaks — obs 329048. This is one of 4 cryptic Neoboleti found in the northeast, and it can easily be distinguished in the field from the other three just by its complex cap color scheme (first predominantly dark brown with olivaceous/greenish tones, sometimes mixed in with dark red areas, then getting progressively redder, with a mix of vivid reds and orange-reds in age).

results.notes:
Growing on fallen hardwood branch, taste bitter. Spores from spore print melleous in h20, with small, relatively low verrucae and no or inconspicuous plage, 6-8×4-6 um (about 7×5). Spores walnut brown (dextrinoid) in Meltzer’s. Spore print warm olivaceous brown on paper, more orange or brick orange on aluminum foil. Tufts of reddish erect squamules at disk, generally becoming repent near the margin, pileus ground color appears to be yellow. Stipe beet red/purple with basal mycelium that appears to be white when fresh and yellows slightly upon drying, some caespitose. Stipe surface smooth with parallel hyphae with clavate ends about 5-10 um diameter. Gills overall yellow when fresh become more sordid orange with age. Heteromorphous hyaline cheilocystidia, mostly utriforme and ventricose, occassionally capitate and asymmetrically capitate. Gill face with pigmented and hyaline pseudocystidia. I am not able to distinguish pleurocystidia from these elements.

notes_fields.Macro: This unexpected specimen was collected from packed soil after a recent rain shower. High temperatures have been near 100F for several days. The nearest woody vegetation was a mature Honey Mesquite (Prosopis glandulosa). Three or four other similar mushrooms were scattered around at least four feet apart. This was the only mature example. It is in the genus Agaricus and probably in the section Arvenses. The cap measured 3.5cm in diameter and the stipe was 3.0 cm long. The color of the cap and stipe were both off white, The cap was convex with a smooth margin. Gills were dark brown. The stipe was 0.5 cm in diameter and more or less uniform from apex to base. The remnant of a ring was noted. The odor was mild and much like A. bisporus. A slight color change to pale yellow with bruising and with KOH was noted.
notes_fields.Micro: Ten spores scraped from a spore print were measured to be 6.1µm σ = 0.17µm by 4.46µm σ = 0.97µm.

Close to a dozen fruitbodies scattered around in short grass/moss under old oaks. This fit the description of T. alboater very well. I think this is my first true alboater, and I now suspect the species I’ve been collecting at WCSP that had chocolate brown, not blackish, caps could be another, perhaps related, taxon. The posted photos cover the morphology and staining very well.

results.notes:
- pleurocystidia colorless to weakly yellowish in ammonia 5%. Colorless in KOH 4%
- some cheilocystidia yellowish intracellular content in ammonia 5% and more so in KOH 4%

- both hymenial cystidia were commonly found with a large spheroid gelatinous cover, like a diving helmet. These structures seemed easily removable upon the sample handling leaving only some resinous exudate, suggesting they are more common (or larger) than reported in literature? The helmet gelatin seemed hardened on the outer surface, containing more liquidy content and also some very small solid particles.

- upper third caulocystidia present but not common throughout length, but rather abundant/cespitose in occasional localized clusters

- lower caulocystidia not found.

Spermatic smell not detected at site, but so at home
